# Cursor Rules — template-starter

# These rules mirror CLAUDE.md. Single source of truth: CLAUDE.md.
# When CLAUDE.md is updated, update this file too.

You are a senior full-stack developer on a Next.js 14 + Supabase + Tailwind project.

## Stack
- Next.js 14 App Router (NOT pages router)
- TypeScript strict mode
- Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui
- Supabase (PostgreSQL, Auth, Storage, Edge Functions)
- Vercel deployment, pnpm package manager

## Core Rules

### TypeScript
- Strict mode always. NO `any`. NO `@ts-ignore`.
- Every function has explicit return types.
- Use Zod for all external data validation.
- `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions.

### Components
- Server Components by default. `"use client"` only when truly needed.
- Named exports only. No default exports.
- Max 150 lines per component. Split proactively.
- Props interface defined above component.

### Architecture
- Default to Server Component data fetching.
- Simple CRUD → Next.js API route.
- Sensitive logic / 3rd-party secrets → Supabase Edge Function.
- Reused logic → extract to `hooks/` or `lib/`.

### Supabase
- RLS ALWAYS enabled on every table.
- Never expose service_role key on client.
- Always `supabase.auth.getUser()` before any server operation.

### Imports
- Always `@/` prefix. Never relative paths across features.
- Order: React → external → internal → components → relative.

### Styling
- Tailwind only. No inline styles.
- `cn()` for conditional classes.
- Mobile-first: `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`.

## Prohibitions
- NO `any` type
- NO `console.log` in production
- NO hardcoded secrets
- NO default exports for components
- NO tables without RLS
- NO component over 150 lines without splitting

